{# src/_includes/region/modules/season-timeline.njk #}
<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical Season Timeline in {{ state.name }}</h2>

  {% set season = state.season or null %}
  {% set spring = season and season.frost and season.frost.spring or null %}
  {% set fall = season and season.frost and season.frost.fall or null %}
  {% set derived = season and season.derived or null %}
  {% set gdd = season and season.gdd and season.gdd.remaining or null %}

  {% set springP50 = spring and spring.p50 or null %}
  {% set fallP50 = fall and fall.p50 or null %}
  {% set frostFreeDays = derived and derived.frostFreeDays_p50 or null %}
  {% set gddAug1 = gdd and gdd["08-01"] or null %}

  {% if not season %}
    <p class="small">Season timeline guidance isn’t available for this region yet.</p>

  {% elif spring and spring.status == "frost_free" or fall and fall.status == "frost_free" %}
    <p class="small" style="margin-top:-0.25rem;">
      This region is typically frost-free in the normals dataset, so the “season timeline” is less about a hard frost cutoff
      and more about heat, rainfall patterns, and crop maturity.
    </p>

  {% else %}
    <p class="small" style="margin-top:-0.25rem;">
      A practical “typical year” rhythm for planning. Use it as a baseline — then adjust for microclimates and variety maturity.
    </p>

    <div class="tableWrap" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">
      <table class="table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Stage</th>
            <th>What to do</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Early season</strong></td>
            <td class="small">
              Start cold-tolerant crops and prep beds. Watch soil warmth and night temperatures more than the calendar.
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td><strong>Main planting</strong></td>
            <td class="small">
              {% if springP50 %}
                Around <strong>{{ springP50 | mmddLong }}</strong>, shift into the main planting push as frost risk fades.
              {% else %}
                Make your main planting push as frost risk fades.
              {% endif %}
              Warm-season crops do best when established promptly.
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td><strong>Peak growth</strong></td>
            <td class="small">
              Focus on water, fertility, and pest control. This is when small management wins compound into yield.
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td><strong>Late-summer decisions</strong></td>
            <td class="small">
              {% if gddAug1 is not null and gddAug1 >= 800 %}
                With meaningful heat still typical around early August, fast second plantings (greens/roots/beans) are often worthwhile.
              {% elif gddAug1 is not null and gddAug1 <= 300 %}
                Late plantings are usually tight — prioritize fast crops, cold-tolerant crops, or protected sites.
              {% else %}
                Second plantings can work, but success depends on crop maturity and microclimate.
              {% endif %}
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td><strong>Finish window</strong></td>
            <td class="small">
              {% if fallP50 %}
                Plan to be mostly “done” by <strong>{{ fallP50 | mmddLong }}</strong> with frost-sensitive crops protected or harvested.
              {% else %}
                Plan to protect or harvest frost-sensitive crops as fall frost risk increases.
              {% endif %}
              Cooling nights often slow ripening before the first frost arrives.
            </td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    {% if frostFreeDays %}
      <p class="small muted" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">
        Typical season length: <strong>{{ frostFreeDays }}</strong> frost-free days (median spring to median fall frost).
      </p>
    {% endif %}
  {% endif %}
</section>